-> Python Dictionaries

A dictionary is used to store data values in key:value pairs. Dictionaries are ordered*, changeable (mutable), and DO NOT allow duplicate keys.

Dictionaries are written with curly brackets `{}` and have keys and values.

1) Creating a Dictionary
   thisdict = {
       "brand": "Ford",
       "model": "Mustang",
       "year": 1964
   }
   print(thisdict)  # Output: {'brand': 'Ford', 'model': 'Mustang', 'year': 1964}

2) Accessing Items (Using key name)
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang"}
   print(thisdict["model"])  # Output: Mustang

3) Changing / Updating Values
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang", "year": 1964}
   thisdict["year"] = 2020
   print(thisdict["year"])  # Output: 2020

4) Adding New Items
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang"}
   thisdict["color"] = "red"
   print(thisdict)  # Output: {'brand': 'Ford', 'model': 'Mustang', 'color': 'red'}

5) Removing Items
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang", "year": 1964}
   thisdict.pop("model")  # Removes the "model" key
   print(thisdict)

6) Checking Dictionary Length
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang", "year": 1964}
   print(len(thisdict))  # Output: 3

7) Looping Through a Dictionary
   thisdict = {"brand": "Ford", "model": "Mustang"}
   
   # Print all key names:
   for key in thisdict:
       print(key)

   # Print all values:
   for value in thisdict.values():
       print(value)

   # Print both keys and values:
   for key, value in thisdict.items():
       print(key, value)
